*1ï¸âƒ£ What is the DOM?*  
The *DOM (Document Object Model)* represents your HTML page as a tree of objects. JavaScript can read/change it to make your page dynamic.

Example â€“ Change text of an element:
```javascript
document.getElementById("title").innerText = "Hello, World!";
```

â–¶ï¸ You can select elements by ID, class, tag, etc.

*2ï¸âƒ£ Event Handling â€“ Making Web Pages Interactive*  
Add actions when users click, hover, type, etc.

```javascript
document.getElementById("btn").addEventListener("click", function() {
  alert("Button clicked!");
});
```

â–¶ï¸ Events include `click`, `mouseover`, `keydown`, `submit`, etc.

*3ï¸âƒ£ Changing Styles with JavaScript*

```javascript
document.getElementById("box").style.backgroundColor = "blue";
```

â–¶ï¸ Use `.style` to dynamically change CSS.

*4ï¸âƒ£ Basic Animation with setInterval*

```javascript
let pos = 0;
let box = document.getElementById("box");

let move = setInterval(() => {
  if (pos >= 200) clearInterval(move);
  else {
    pos += 5;
    box.style.left = pos + "px";
  }
}, 50);
```

â–¶ï¸ Moves a box 200px to the right in steps.

